[[The Stranglewood]]'s Ritual Site is located north-west of the forest. The site can be accessed by climbing over [[rocks (Vardorvis)|rocks]] leading to it. After entering the Ritual Site once, a shortcut on the pathway north-west of the temple can be used to reach Vardorvis quicker.

The fastest way to get to Vardorvis is the teleport to "The Stranglewood" on the [[ring of shadows]], once it has been unlocked with the [[strangled tablet]]. Other fast options include the {{Fairycode|bls}} [[fairy ring]] or the [[Xeric's talisman]] (with the Xeric's Honour teleport to [[Mount Quidamortem]] unlocked), which both give quick access to the [[Rowboat (Great Kourend)|rowboat]] that connects the [[Kebos Lowlands]] to The Stranglewood.

An [[Ancient Tablet (Vardorvis)|ancient tablet]] by the rocks leading to the Ritual Site shows statistics related to Vardorvis.

==History==
[[File:Statue (Vardorvis).png|thumb|left|180px|The statue of Carnifex Maximus Vardorvis in the Ancient Vault.]]
Vardorvis was a [[vampyre]] who served the [[Zarosian Empire]] under the rank of Carnifex Maximus, whose role was that of an executioner or headsman.{{CiteNPC|npc=Ghost (Ruins of Camdozaal)|quote=Useless! Perhaps the headsman needs to take your head as well.}} He was one of four individuals entrusted with a medallion - the means to open the [[Ancient Vault]] where the [[Elder Horn]] was sealed - alongside [[Perseriya]], [[Duke Sucellus]], and [[the Whisperer]], who were all high-ranking personnel in the Empire.

At some point during the [[Third Age]], after the [[Betrayal of Zaros]], he was deployed to [[Lassar]] to defend the fortress from a siege by [[Saradomin]]ists. This included the [[Imcando dwarves]], who pledged their allegiance to Saradomin in exchange for a new settlement after their previous home, [[Imcandoria]], was destroyed.{{CiteNPC|npc=Ghost (Ruins of Camdozaal)|quote=The city [Imcandoria] fell and now they are homeless.}}{{CiteNPC|npc=Ghost (Ruins of Camdozaal)|quote=It seems [the Imcando] have been promised a new home here in return for wiping us out.}} His presence was likely to also instill some discipline in the troops, executing those who refused orders or were incompetent.{{CiteNPC|npc=Ghost (Ruins of Camdozaal)|quote=Useless! Perhaps the headsman needs to take your head as well.}}

During the siege, Vardorvis was also tasked with executing the opposing leader, [[Yonrith Lovakengj]]. Yonrith was able to escape and fled west with some of his closest allies to [[Zeah]]. Though Vardorvis claimed that Yonrith was a threat to the Empty Lord, some of his subordinates believed that his pride was wounded when Yonrith was able to escape his axes.{{CiteText|text=Tatty page|quote=He claims the target to be a danger to the Empire who cannot be allowed to live, but it's hard to ignore the role the Carnifex Maximus' pride may be playing. After all, this is the first time anyone has escaped his axe.}} Vardorvis brought a small force to pursue him all the way to the western continent,{{CiteNPC|npc=Ghost (Ruins of Camdozaal)|quote=Their leader is named Yonrith Lovakengj. He has fled to the west with his closest allies, but much of his army still remains. Carnifex Maximus Vardorvis is in pursuit of him.}} and made camp in what is now known as [[the Stranglewood]].

On the sixth day of their pursuit, Vardorvis' venators successfully located the Imcando dwarves.{{CiteText|text=Tatty page|quote=The timing couldn't be worse, for the venators have also located the dwarves.}} However, one of Vardorvis' subordinates, interested in studying [[the Strangler]], accidentally infected him with a sample of the parasite on the same day.{{CiteText|text=Tatty page|quote=It seems my eagerness may have come at a cost. The sample I collected from the ritual site was carrying some sort of parasite, and of course, it was the Carnifex Maximus himself who ended up getting infected.}} Due to his vampyric nature, Vardorvis was not worried until the subordinate informed him that it could potentially kill.{{CiteText|text=Tatty page|quote=He showed little interest in my work, right until I told him it had the potential to kill. That got his attention right away.}}

The next day, the dwarves tracked the venators to their camp and launched a surprise attack{{CiteText|text=Tatty page|quote=They attacked! The dwarves must have tracked the venators, for they found our camp with ease. Most of our party is dead or injured...}}, [[Vardorvis' Head|beheading]] the Carnifex Maximus during the skirmish, as the parasite removed his immunity to non-silver/blisterwood weaponry.{{CiteText|text=Tatty page|quote=They took his head clean off! He's a vampyre! It shouldn't have been possible, but they did it all the same! The parasite must be to blame.}} The parasite proceeded to move Vardorvis' body, head and axes to the ritual site, which was observed by a legionary{{CiteText|text=Tatty page|quote=The parasite must be to blame. It's far more dangerous than we thought, and I fear others may be infected as well. Many have claimed to be feeling strangely unwell, and one of the legionaries even started having visions. Of all things, he thought he saw the Carnifex Maximus' body move!}}, and would remain there for thousands of years.

During the [[Fifth Age]], an [[player character|adventurer]] who sought his medallion eventually found Vardorvis in the Stranglewood and attacked him, believing that he had the medallion on him. Despite the plague making use of Vardorvis' numerous abilities, the adventurer put him down, but discovered that the medallion was not on him - rather, it had been taken by Sliske, who disguised himself as [[Kasonde]]. The parasite proceeded to reanimate Vardorvis when the adventurer left.

==Fight overview==
{{Main|Vardorvis/Strategies}}
Vardorvis uses a standard melee attack, which is reduced by roughly ~75% when [[Protect from Melee]] is active; regardless, he will heal for 50% of the damage inflicted, rounded down. Unlike the other members of the Forgotten Four, who use their special attacks in a rather slow and predictable manner, Vardorvis uses them at random. Some of these attacks are additionally extended the lower his health is, making the fight more hectic.

[[File:Fighting Vardorvis.png|left|thumb|A player fighting Vardorvis.]]
In addition, Vardorvis' Strength and Defence levels scale linearly with his remaining hitpoints; as his health falls, his Defence level is lowered while his Strength level is increased, increasing the potency of his auto-attacks though making him easier to hit.<ref>The amount of defence reduction at any given amount of damage dealt can be calculated using<math>defence reduction = round(0.1021*damage dealt - 0.2075)</math> - [https://imgur.com/a/ppJmNOl source]</ref> Vardorvis' mechanics are adjusted accordingly as his health lowers.

Vardorvis uses the following special attacks:
* '''Swinging Axes''': The Strangler's vines will swing up to three axes within the arena. Getting hit with this attack will deal up to 35 damage, and incur a damage-over-time "bleed" effect in which the player takes 3 bleed damage 5 times (more than 5 times if the player moves while bleeding). The bleed will persist even through teleportation. Using [[Protect from Melee]] will reduce the axes' initial hit by 50%, but will not reduce damage from the bleed.
* '''Strangle''': Vardorvis will strike his arm into the ground and entangle the player in tendrils. Several spores will appear at the centre of the game screen, and the player must destroy them all within five seconds, otherwise the tendrils will tighten and deal high damage.
* '''Head Gaze''': The Strangler's vines will use [[Vardorvis' Head]] to launch a single green projectile. If this projectile is not blocked with [[Protect from Missiles]], <u>it will disable overhead protection prayers</u> and drain the player's prayer points by 10. Vardorvis will not melee while the projectile is in the air, and will take exactly two ticks to melee the player once the projectile has hit. Failing to react properly to a projectile can lead to a chain reaction that often kills inexperienced players due to the panicked prayer swapping that ensues. If you do not react to the projectile in time, immediately turn [[Protect from Melee|Protect Melee]] back on (he will always melee next), watch your feet (as he can use Darting Spikes at random), and heal back up. 
** It is difficult, however if you are quick enough you can ''"tag-all"'' [[Vardorvis' Head]] (if on the RuneLite client) to more conveniently see when it pops out of the ground. His head is coded as a separate NPC, and will take on a different tag color if you manage to assign it, though the timing window is very small.
* '''Darting Spikes''': Vardorvis will dart around the player, causing cracks to appear. Vines will then erupt from them, dealing up to 25 damage if caught in one and healing him for half the amount. Vardorvis can dart up to three times. A crack will always appear under the player on the first dart unless they are standing by the edges of the arena. Vardorvis will launch a singular spike at the player if he is somehow unable to attack them.

Upon reaching 33% of his health, Vardorvis will enter an enrage phase, significantly increasing the frequency of his special attacks.

[[File:Vardorvis reviving.mp4|thumb|Vardorvis reviving]]
Vardorvis respawns after 10 seconds upon dying.

